        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirements: 

We expect that the CO flux emission, measured by APEX, comes from a
region of 2x1 arcsec^2 (400x200 parsec^2 at source redshift) corresponding to the disk region of high  extinction seen in HST
observations.
In order to image in the finest detail the CO emission 
we ask for the highest spatial resolution of about 0.18
arcsec (corresponding to 36 pc). The largest size is 
expected to be &lt;3.75 arcsec, making unecessary observing with ACA.

Requested sensitivity: 

The primary goal of the present proposal is the spectral analysis 
of the 12CO(2-1) emission line.  From our APEX 12CO(2-1) line
observation we obtain an integrated line flux of 63 Jy*km\s  for
 NGC3557, or a peak flux density of 250 mJy for a characteristic
 line width of 250km\s. 
Under the hypothesis that the majority of the CO emission comes from
the molecular gas coinciding with the high-extinction part of the
dust disk (2x1 arcsec^2), the expected flux densities per beam 
 is 4.1mJy. Since we aim for a 5 SN detection in the wings of the
 line, say a factor of 3 below the peak flux density, we ask for 
a sensitivity 0.25 mJy\beam. 

We require a spectral resolution of 25 km\s in order to sample 
the line in 20 independent spectral elements across the wings to
determine an adequate rotation curve. These specifications call 
for about 1.7 hours on-source integration time. 

Assuming that the HST dust disk mass is about 1% of the dust mass
estimated from IRAS observations (following the IRAS-HST dust
 mass correlation found for B2 radio galaxies by deRuiter 2002), 
we estimate a dust continuum flux density for NGC3557 of  S(nu)=1
 mJy at 230 GHz. Here we assume that S(nu)=k(nu) M(dust)B(nu,T)/D^2,
 where k(nu)=0.07kg\m is the dust absorption coefficient; 
M(dust)= 0.01 M(dust-IRAS)=10^(3.6)xM; B(nu,T) is the Planck
function; D is the galaxy distance and T = 20K is the dust
temperature (Smith 2012).  For a total bandwidth of 7.25 GHz
(excluding the CO line) the rms noise level in 1.7 hours is
0.01 mJy\beam. Thus, if the dust is spread uniformly over
the disk (the worst case), we would not expect to be able to 
image the disk accurately at full resolution, where the expected
 brightness is 0.015 mJy\beam, but we should be able to achieve a detection by tapering to a beam of 0.5arcsec FWHM. We note, however,
 that there is a very large scatter in the IRAS-HST dust mass relation, so the flux density could be significantly larger or smaller than we assume.

There are no measurements of the radio core flux density of NGC3557
at high frequencies, but it shows a rising radio spectrum (proportional to nu^0.56), with flux-density measurements of 13, 24 and 27 mJy at 2.3, 4.9 and 8.4GHz respectively (Slee et al 1994}). Guessing that the radio spectrum rises monotonically up to a frequency of about 30 GHz, and then turns over with  nu^{-1} (typical of brighter cores), we expect a flux density of about 7 mJy at 230 GHz. Such a core source would be unresolved and bright enough to use for phase self-calibration with a solution interval of about 1 min.

Correlator setup: 

The primary goal of this proposal is imaging of the 12CO(2-1) emission line. We have therefore centered one of the four available spectral windows at the frequency of the redshifted 12CO(2-1) line (228.23179GHz).  The expected FWHM is about 250 km\s, with a full width of about 500 km\s (see Fig. 1), so we do not require very high spectral resolution  (spectral resolution of 25km\s is enough for our purposesto determine a rotation curve). We have therefore chosen the FDM set-up with the largest bandwidth (1.875 GHz) to get a reliable continuum image and to search fot high-velocity gas (infalling and outflowing).
The other three spectral windows are instead optimized for continuum observations (TDM set-up, 2 GHz bandwidth), as we are interested in detecting the continuum dust disk emission and/or the radio core continuum.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
