    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Galaxy formation theories struggle to explain the quenching of star formation and the formation of substructures in early-type galaxies (ETG). The solutions to both may well be connected. Molecular gas can feed active galactic nuclei and generate feedback, while also leading to new decoupled stellar components. We have gathered VLT/VIMOS Integral Field Unit spectroscopy for a complete  volume-limited (z&lt;0.03) sample of 11 southern radio galaxies (RG). All RGs have been also observed and detected in 12CO(2-1) line with APEX-1. With the current proposal we ask to start the CO imaging follow-up of the sample, with pilot observations of a first target: NGC 3557. Our sample of RGs (in which jets are currently active), will provide a crucial comparison with existing studies of radio-quiet ETGs and allow us to isolate the role played by AGN jet feedback in the overall formation and evolutionary scenario of ETGs.
ALMA is ideal for the proposed mapping, and our sample is appropriately sized for a first study aiming to identify common trends.</prp:abstract>
